  "slug": "the-top-five-performances-of-2024-plus-the-amy-adams-hall-of",
  "title": "The Top Five Performances of 2024. Plus: The Amy Adams Hall of Fame and ‘Nightbitch.’",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Rob Mahoney",
    "Joanna Robinson"
  ],
  "published": "2024-12-16",
  "runtimeMin": 136,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey, Rob Mahoney, and Joanna Robinson each rank five favorite performances of 2024, then run a long honorable-mentions roundtable. They review Marielle Heller's 'Nightbitch' and build a ten-film Amy Adams Hall of Fame. Sean closes with an interview with Pablo Larraín about 'María.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Rob Mahoney's Top Five Performances of 2024",
      "note": "No. 1 first",
      "subject": "performances of 2024",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Challengers",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 1: Josh O'Connor as a perfect cad and shitheel; the alleyway scene where he asks Zendaya to coach him. Rob's favorite performance in one of his favorite movies of the year. God's Own Country and The Crown already proved he can do anything."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anora",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 2: Mikey Madison, transformative and relentless in a role that could grate if pitched slightly differently. Rob had little Madison exposure before and left fully signed up."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dìdi",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 3: Joan Chen as the coming-of-age mom: funny, controlling, quietly wrecked. The scene where she demythologizes Dìdi in front of his older skater friends is punishingly real."
        },
        {
          "title": "Alien: Romulus",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 4: David Jonsson as the synthetic Andy, reprogrammed and degraded across the movie; the defining performance in it, in the Fassbender lineage of humanizing a machine."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune: Part Two",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 5 (the lick-a-knife rule): Austin Butler's Feyd-Rautha stealing a stacked movie; let him be a freak more often. Rob's verdict on release: 'that was sick.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Joanna Robinson's Top Five Performances of 2024",
      "note": "No. 1 first",
      "subject": "performances of 2024",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sing Sing",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 1: Colman Domingo holding the center among nonprofessional actors as an incarcerated theater-group leader who hits a crisis of faith; the small window to the outside he keeps returning to. One of our great actors taking this project as his star rose."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gladiator II",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 2: Denzel Washington as Macrinus: a synthesis of Training Day, Glory, and the goofier early stuff, Shakespearean and wily with a sexual fluidity under the surface. Saves a movie Jo otherwise didn't enjoy."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anora",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 3 (scene stealer): Yura Borisov as Igor, magnetic with little dialogue as the camera lingers on him watching. Jo did a full rewatch just tracking him."
        },
        {
          "title": "Deadpool & Wolverine",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 4 ('you really didn't need to go that hard'): Emma Corrin as Cassandra Nova, gleefully creepy hand-in-the-head physicality in a movie the hosts had fun with but don't think is good."
        },
        {
          "title": "My Old Ass",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 5 (newcomer): Maisie Stella holding down a movie mispackaged as an Aubrey Plaza two-hander. Engaging, occasionally unlikable, easy to root for, and game for a full Justin Bieber fantasy sequence."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Sean Fennessey's Top Five Performances of 2024",
      "note": "No. 1 first; his No. 5 is a two-movie slot",
      "subject": "performances of 2024",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sing Sing",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 1: Clarence Maclin as Divine Eye, the co-lead: a nonprofessional actor and former RTA participant. He and Domingo swap places like a double helix; the late scenes between them are the movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "The First Omen",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 2: Nell Tiger Free, a discovery, as a nun slowly becoming possessed, matching Arkasha Stevenson's vision. (Once played Princess Myrcella on Game of Thrones.)"
        },
        {
          "title": "Hard Truths",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 3: Marianne Jean-Baptiste's Mike Leigh reunion (their first since Secrets & Lies), a sustained, fearless portrait of anger. The couch-shopping scene builds empathy without redemption."
        },
        {
          "title": "Heretic",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 4: Hugh Grant as Mr. Reed, the culmination of his 'piece of shit' era: aw-shucks bumbling turned chilling, bouncing off Sophie Thatcher and Chloe East. Two-thirds perfect."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Quiet Place: Day One",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 5 (shared slot): Lupita Nyong'o as a woman in hospice at the end of the world; the survival-movie register that rarely gets awarded."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Wild Robot",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "No. 5 (shared slot): Lupita Nyong'o again, a vocal performance putting a character into the robot essence: the hidden art of voice acting."
        }
      ]
    },
