    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Nightbitch’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Nightbitch",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Marielle Heller's adaptation of the Rachel Yoder novel, with Amy Adams and Scoot McNairy: a mother alone all day with a two-year-old who begins turning into a dog. All three praise the monotony and alienation of early motherhood as unnervingly accurate (Sean, a parent, felt seen), and Adams's haggard, all-in performance. Their shared reservation: the genre trimmings and the tidy end-of-movie speech and art show pull the edges off. Sean's wife texted 'this movie is so rough' mid-watch. Compared to Tully and, on its 'laurels to the artist' ending, The Brutalist."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "halloffame",
      "heading": "The Amy Adams Hall of Fame",
      "honoree": "Amy Adams",
      "note": "the ten inducted films, after grading her filmography green, yellow, or red",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Catch Me If You Can",
          "year": 2002,
          "role": "Brenda Strong",
          "note": "First green. A tiny part, but she's unmistakable: 'show me a better performance in braces.' Her only film with Leo, so far."
        },
        {
          "title": "Junebug",
          "year": 2005,
          "role": "Ashley",
          "note": "The major breakthrough: the sweet, pregnant, wide-eyed innocent. Won at Sundance, first Oscar nomination. The naivety engine in full effect."
        },
        {
          "title": "Enchanted",
          "year": 2007,
          "role": "Giselle",
          "note": "Indisputable. One of her biggest hits, built entirely on her charm after Junebug. The first live-action Disney princess not drawn from harnessed IP. Marsden almost steals it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Miss Pettigrew Lives for a Day",
          "year": 2008,
          "role": "Delysia Lafosse",
          "note": "'So green. Go to bed.' Maybe as charming as she's ever been: a live-wire, incorrigible flirt opposite Frances McDormand's straight woman."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Fighter",
          "year": 2010,
          "role": "Charlene Fleming",
          "note": "Her scrappiest, most against-type turn; second Oscar nomination. The porch fight is her one clip-reel moment. Melissa Leo's campaign beat her that year."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Master",
          "year": 2012,
          "role": "Peggy Dodd",
          "note": "A wife part, but she does far more with it: a woman quietly, at times overwhelmingly, in control of the frame. If you like The Brutalist, watch this first."
        },
        {
          "title": "American Hustle",
          "year": 2013,
          "role": "Sydney Prosser",
          "note": "Auto-green for her even though the hosts don't love the movie: the part-within-a-part layering of accents. Her most financially successful non-franchise hit; another Oscar nomination."
        },
        {
          "title": "Arrival",
          "year": 2016,
          "role": "Louise Banks",
          "note": "The number one: likely the best movie she's made, carried 80 percent by her acting opposite a window. Sean argues she should have won; the Meryl-in-Florence-Foster-Jenkins nomination that year is 'a joke.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Nocturnal Animals",
          "year": 2016,
          "role": "Susan Morrow",
          "note": "Granted 'for you and the state of Texas,' Joanna and Rob's charitable push. Tom Ford's mean, knowing trash; her reading of the manuscript is the whole exercise. (Also the debut of the Aaron Taylor-Johnson six-pack.)"
        },
        {
          "title": "Nightbitch",
          "year": 2024,
          "role": "Mother",
          "note": "The tenth slot, over Doubt and Big Eyes: there's no movie without her, and she produced it. Her 'do it myself' producer era, closing the loop on the Junebug expecting-mother arc."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Pablo Larraín on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "María",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The third of Larraín's accidental trilogy of women, after Jackie and Spencer, with Angelina Jolie as Maria Callas. An opera fan since childhood, he wanted a film that is an opera 'in motion': a moving proscenium set in Callas's last week. He opens on Jolie singing Ave Maria in close-up to 'defeat the ghost' of the casting in the first minute. On why biopics are 'a cultural fantasy,' the enigma-plus-magnetism he saw in both Jolie and Callas, shooting on film with cinematographer Ed Lachman (after El Conde) to work through color, and the vanished mid-century world of art, money, and glamour. His last great thing seen: Anora."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
